Preprocessing of Raw Data#

This preprocessing step is important to delete noise, standarize data and guarantee a quality analysis for the single cell RNA sequencing.

Quality control metrics#

üìå Quality Control (QC) Metrics in scRNA-seq#

1Ô∏è‚É£ Number of Cells Expressing Each Gene (gene_counts)

  • Measures how widely expressed each gene is across cells.

  • Genes expressed in very few cells may be technical noise.

  • Helps decide which genes to keep in downstream analysis.

2Ô∏è‚É£ Number of Detected Genes per Cell (n_genes_by_cell)

  • Indicates the complexity of RNA content in each cell.

  • Low values suggest dead cells or empty droplets.

  • High values may indicate doublets (two cells captured together).

3Ô∏è‚É£ Total UMI Counts per Cell (total_UMI_counts)

  • Represents the sequencing depth per cell.

  • Low counts suggest poor RNA capture or damaged cells.

  • High counts can indicate doublets or highly active cells.

üîç These metrics help identify low-quality cells before filtering.

adata_glioblastoma_raw.var['gene_count'] = np.array((adata_glioblastoma_raw.X > 0).sum(axis=0)).flatten()
adata_glioblastoma_raw.obs['n_genes_by_cell'] = (adata_glioblastoma_raw.X > 0).sum(axis=1)
adata_glioblastoma_raw.obs['total_UMI_counts'] = adata_glioblastoma_raw.X.sum(axis=1)

üß¨ Unique Molecular Identifiers (UMIs)#

What is a UMI?#

A Unique Molecular Identifier (UMI) is a short random barcode added to RNA molecules before sequencing.
UMIs help correct for PCR amplification bias and improve the accuracy of gene expression quantification in single-cell RNA sequencing (scRNA-seq).

Why Are UMIs Important?#

1Ô∏è‚É£ Reduce PCR Bias ‚Üí Prevents artificially inflated gene expression caused by PCR duplicates.
2Ô∏è‚É£ Improve Quantification ‚Üí Counts only unique UMIs, not sequencing reads, for accurate expression levels.
3Ô∏è‚É£ Remove Technical Noise ‚Üí Helps correct sequencing errors and distinguish true biological signals.

How Are UMIs Used in scRNA-seq?#

  • Low UMI counts ‚Üí Suggests low RNA content, dead cells, or empty droplets.

  • High UMI counts ‚Üí Could indicate doublets (two cells captured together).

  • UMI filtering ensures that only high-quality data is used in downstream analysis.

UMIs improve scRNA-seq accuracy by eliminating technical biases. üöÄ

# Plot histogram of total UMI counts per cell
sns.histplot(adata_glioblastoma_raw.obs['total_UMI_counts'], bins = 50, kde=True)

Cell filtering#

Why Do We Filter Cells?#

We remove cells that are:
1Ô∏è‚É£ Low-quality or dead ‚Üí Few detected genes or low UMI counts.
2Ô∏è‚É£ Potential doublets ‚Üí Abnormally high UMI counts (two cells captured together).
3Ô∏è‚É£ Stressed or apoptotic ‚Üí High percentage of mitochondrial RNA.

üìä How Do We Define Filtering Thresholds?#

We use three key QC metrics:

Metric

Issue Detected

Filtering Rule

Total UMI Counts

Low = Empty droplets, debris
High = Possible doublets

Keep cells with a moderate range of UMI counts

Number of Genes per Cell

Low = Dead/low-quality cells
High = Doublets

Set lower/upper cutoffs based on distribution

Mitochondrial Gene Percentage

High = Cell stress, apoptosis

Remove cells with too high mito RNA%

 
mito_genes = adata_glioblastoma_raw.var_names.str.startswith('MT-')
adata_glioblastoma_raw.obs['percent_mito'] = (adata_glioblastoma_raw[:, mito_genes].X.sum(axis=1) / 
                                              adata_glioblastoma_raw.obs['total_UMI_counts']) * 100

# Set filtering thresholds
min_genes = 200     # Remove cells with fewer than 200 genes
max_genes = 5000    # Remove cells with more than 5000 genes (possible doublets)
min_UMI = 500       # Remove cells with very low UMI counts (empty droplets)
max_mito = 10       # Remove cells with >10% mitochondrial RNA

# Apply filtering
filtered_cells = (adata_glioblastoma_raw.obs['n_genes_by_cell'] > min_genes) & \
                 (adata_glioblastoma_raw.obs['n_genes_by_cell'] < max_genes) & \
                 (adata_glioblastoma_raw.obs['total_UMI_counts'] > min_UMI) & \
                 (adata_glioblastoma_raw.obs['percent_mito'] < max_mito)

# Filter and display mitochondrial gene names from the dataset
mito_genes_list = [gene for gene in adata_glioblastoma_raw.var_names if 'MT' in gene.upper()]
print(mito_genes_list[:20])  # Print the first 20 mitochondrial genes

import mygene

# Initialize MyGeneInfo client
mg = mygene.MyGeneInfo()

# Load your mapped gene list dynamically (assuming it's a dictionary or list)
gene_list = list(gene_mappings.keys())  # Extract gene symbols from gene_mappings

# Query gene information in batches to avoid API limits
batch_size = 1000
mitochondrial_genes = []
mitochondrial_prefixes = set()

for i in range(0, len(gene_list), batch_size):
    batch = gene_list[i:i + batch_size]
    results = mg.querymany(batch, scopes="symbol", fields="go", species="human", verbose=False)

    for gene in results:
        if "go" in gene and "Cellular component" in gene["go"]:
            for entry in gene["go"]["Cellular component"]:
                if "mitochondrion" in entry["term"].lower():
                    mitochondrial_genes.append(gene["query"])
                    mitochondrial_prefixes.add(gene["query"][:3])  # Store first 3 letters

# Print results
print("Mitochondrial gene prefixes:", list(mitochondrial_prefixes))
print("Number of mitochondrial genes:", len(mitochondrial_genes))

Doublets and Singlets in Single-Cell RNA-Seq (scRNA-Seq)#

In single-cell RNA sequencing (scRNA-Seq), the terms ‚Äúdoublet‚Äù and ‚Äúsinglet‚Äù refer to the nature of the captured cells in the experiment:

  • Singlet ‚Üí A single individual cell encapsulated in a droplet or captured in a well.

  • Doublet ‚Üí Two cells encapsulated together in the same droplet, which can lead to contaminated or mixed data in the analysis.

üî¨ Why is it important to detect doublets?#

Doublets can lead to false interpretations in the analysis, as they may appear to be a new cell type with a combined expression profile of two real cells. This affects:

  • Cell type identification (they may seem like new cell types that do not actually exist).

  • Analysis of cellular subpopulations.

  • Inference of cell relationships and trajectories.
